## Task 1 — Mobile Filter Drawer for `/listings`

### Goal
On mobile (< 768px), replace the sidebar filter panel with a bottom-sheet drawer that
slides up from the bottom of the screen when the user taps a "Filters" button. The
filter content is identical — same fields, same state, same URL params — just presented
in a mobile-friendly overlay.

### Implementation

**Step 1.1 — Add a `FilterDrawer` component**

Create `app/components/FilterDrawer.tsx`.

This component:
- Accepts the same filter props/state as the current sidebar (make, model, price range,
  year range, total time, deal type, maintenance burden, priced-only toggle, etc.)
- Renders as a fixed-position overlay that slides up from the bottom of the screen
- Has a visible handle bar at the top (a short horizontal pill/line — standard mobile
  drawer pattern)
- Has a clear "Apply" button and an "×" or "Done" close button
- Has a "Clear all filters" link
- Uses `overflow-y: auto` so the filter content scrolls inside the drawer if tall
- The drawer backdrop (behind the drawer) should be a semi-transparent dark overlay;
  tapping it closes the drawer
- The drawer should be max-height 85vh so it never covers the full screen
- Must work in both dark and light themes — use the existing CSS variables/tokens from
  the theme system already in the codebase (do not hardcode colors)
- Must NOT use any new npm package — implement with CSS transforms and React state only.
  Use `translate-y-full` / `translate-y-0` with a Tailwind transition for the
  slide animation.

**Step 1.2 — Add the "Filters" trigger button to the mobile listings header**

In `app/listings/page.tsx`:
- On mobile (default / no breakpoint prefix), show a sticky "Filters" button in the
  listings header bar. Show an active-filter badge count on the button when any
  non-default filters are applied (e.g. "Filters (3)").
- On desktop (`md:` and above), hide this button — the sidebar is visible instead.
- The sidebar itself should be `hidden md:block` (hidden on mobile, visible on desktop).
- Tapping "Filters" opens the `FilterDrawer`.

**Step 1.3 — Preserve all filter state and URL params**
The drawer must use the exact same URL param handling and filter state as the desktop
sidebar. Do not create a separate state system. The drawer is purely a presentation
layer over the existing filter logic. When the user taps "Apply" or changes a filter,
the URL updates exactly as it does on desktop.

**Step 1.4 — Verify**
- At 390px width: "Filters" button is visible, tapping it opens the drawer, filters
  work, closing the drawer returns to the listings view.
- At 768px+ width: sidebar is visible, "Filters" button is hidden, behavior unchanged.
- URL params update correctly in both modes.
- Dark and light themes both look correct.

