## Task 2 — Listing Detail Page Mobile Polish

### Goal
The listing detail page should be fully readable and functional on a 390px viewport.
No horizontal overflow. Panels in the right priority order.

### Step 2.1 — Fix the Comps chart overflow
In `app/listings/[id]/page.tsx` (or its `CompsChartPanel.tsx` sub-component):
- The chart container must have `w-full overflow-x-hidden` and the chart itself
  must use `width: '100%'` rather than a fixed pixel width.
- The Price-vs-Year / Price-vs-Time toggle tabs should stack or truncate gracefully
  at 390px — use `flex-wrap` if needed.
- The comps data table below the chart: on mobile, hide the less critical columns.
  Keep: Make/Model, Year, Price. Hide on mobile (add `hidden md:table-cell`): TT, SMOH,
  Days on Market. The table must not cause horizontal scroll on the page.

### Step 2.2 — Verify panel stacking order on mobile
On mobile, panels should stack in this priority order (top to bottom):
1. Aircraft header (title, score badge, asking price)
2. Score summary / value score panel
3. Comp & Cost panel (chart)
4. Engine Value panel
5. FAA snapshot
6. Avionics
7. Aircraft Details / description
8. Gallery images

If the current order differs from this on mobile, adjust the flex/grid column ordering
using CSS `order` utilities (`order-1`, `order-2` etc.) applied at the default/mobile
level, with desktop order restored at `md:` breakpoint. Do NOT restructure the DOM
order if it would break desktop layout — use CSS order utilities exclusively.

### Step 2.3 — Image gallery mobile treatment
The gallery images (if rendered as a horizontal row) should become a swipeable
horizontal scroll container on mobile:
```tsx
<div className="flex gap-2 overflow-x-auto snap-x snap-mandatory pb-2 md:grid md:grid-cols-3 md:overflow-visible">
  {images.map(img => (
    <div className="flex-shrink-0 w-72 snap-start md:w-auto" key={img}>
      ...
    </div>
  ))}
</div>
```
This requires no new packages — CSS scroll snap is native browser behavior.

### Step 2.4 — Touch targets
Any button, tab, or interactive element on the listing detail page that is smaller than
44×44px on mobile should have its padding increased via `min-h-[44px] min-w-[44px]`
to meet touch target guidelines. Check: score tier tabs, chart toggle buttons, sort
toggles in the comps table.

